> Feijoada is a meaty version of the Brazilian staple dish of cooked black beans,
> using pork mince to create a beautifully rich flavour. Traditionally prepared
> over a low heat in a clay pot and simmered for an hour, tonight's recipe will
> prove that you can create the same flavour in double quick time. 20 minute
> recipes don't get more delicious than this one!

== Rice ==

Bring a large #saucepan{} of water, with a pinch of @salt{pinch}, to the boil
for the rice.

When boiling, add the @basmati rice{150%g} and cook for ~{10-12%mins}, then drain
in a #sieve{} and return to the saucepan, with the lid on, off the heat.

== Pork Feijoada ==

Heat a #frying pan{} on medium-high heat.

Add the @British pork mince{240%g} and @chorizo{60%g}(diced) (no oil!).

Cook until browned, ~{5%mins}. Break the pork up with a #wooden spoon{} as it
cooks.

Meanwhile, trim the @green beans{150%g} and chop into thirds.

Roughly chop the @coriander{10%g}(stalks and all).

Drain and rinse the @black beans{1} in the sieve.

Lower the heat to medium.

Once the pork has browned, add the green beans, @feijoada paste{25%g} and
@bolognese garnish{10%g} to the pan.

Stir and cook for ~{3%mins}.

Add the @water for the sauce{50%ml}, @finely chopped tomatoes with onion and
garlic{1%jar} and black beans, stir and bring to the boil.

Cover with a #lid{} and simmer until thickened, ~{7%mins}.

Serve the rice topped with the pork feijoada and a sprinkling of coriander.